description: Python conventions
globs: ["**/*.py"]
---
- Python 3.12. Use modern syntax (match/case, walrus, PEP 604 unions: `int | None`).
- Type hints are mandatory on all public functions. Run mypy in strict mode.
- Use Pydantic v2 for all data contracts and config models.
- Use `pathlib.Path`, never `os.path`.
- Prefer composition over inheritance. Dataclasses or Pydantic models, not bare dicts.
- Logging: use `logging.getLogger(__name__)`, never `print` outside notebooks.
- Errors: raise specific exceptions, never bare `except:`.
- Docstrings: Google style on all public functions.
- Tests: pytest with fixtures; one test file per module under `tests/`.
- Lint/format: ruff (line length 100). No black, no isort — ruff handles both.

# Commenting

- Comment WHY, not WHAT. Code shows what; comments explain rationale, trade-offs, gotchas.
- Add a brief comment (1–3 lines) ABOVE any line/block that uses: a non-obvious library idiom, a workaround for a known issue, a performance-motivated choice, a security-sensitive operation, or a regex/cryptic syntax.
- For functions >10 lines, split into logical sections with a single `# Section <section number>: <intent>` header per section.
- Module-level docstring explains purpose, key concepts, and how this module fits the pipeline.
- DO NOT comment trivia (`# increment i`, `# create empty list`).
- DO NOT use end-of-line comments except for very short clarifying notes; place comments on the line above.
- Wrap comments at 100 chars.
